{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"duration_ms":96750,"duration_api_ms":95517,"num_turns":3,"result":"","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"d87d4469-993e-4d5a-9d22-498a8bcd18de","total_cost_usd":0.42815679999999995,"usage":{"input_tokens":4,"cache_creation_input_tokens":35173,"cache_read_input_tokens":66037,"output_tokens":1990,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":35173,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"},"modelUsage":{"claude-opus-4-6":{"inputTokens":4,"outputTokens":1990,"cacheReadInputTokens":66037,"cacheCreationInputTokens":35173,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.30261975,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":64000},"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001":{"inputTokens":117,"outputTokens":4086,"cacheReadInputTokens":592788,"cacheCreationInputTokens":36569,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.12553705,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":32000}},"permission_denials":[],"structured_output":{"rulings":[{"amendment_id":"fr-7-f5efd49b","decision":"reject","rationale":"The amendment's core premise — that reqwest's timeout may not fire during slow-streaming responses because 'bytes are still flowing' — is factually incorrect for `ClientBuilder::timeout()`. reqwest's `timeout()` sets an absolute wall-clock deadline from request start to full body receipt; it does NOT reset when data arrives. The per-read-reset behavior the amendment describes belongs to `read_timeout()`, a separate API not used here. The code at line 105 uses `Client::builder().timeout(request.timeout)` and consumes the response non-streamingly via `response.text().await` (line 243). This means the total timeout will fire after the configured duration regardless of whether the server is trickling data. Therefore `enforces_timeout() -> true` (line 359) is semantically correct — the adapter does provide a hard wall-clock guarantee, and the 30-second service buffer (service.rs lines 204-213) is granted under a valid premise. Reviewer 2's analysis citing reqwest's documented distinction between `timeout()` (total deadline) and `read_timeout()` (per-chunk reset) is authoritative and tips the balance toward rejection."}],"summary":"Rejected fr-7-f5efd49b. The amendment incorrectly claims reqwest's `ClientBuilder::timeout()` may fail to fire during trickle-streaming. In fact, `timeout()` is an absolute wall-clock deadline unaffected by data flow — the per-read reset behavior described belongs to `read_timeout()`, a different API. Since the OpenRouterBackendAdapter uses `timeout()` and consumes the response non-streamingly via `.text().await`, its `enforces_timeout() -> true` is correct and the service's 30-second buffer is appropriately granted."},"fast_mode_state":"off","uuid":"415c4e5e-1eff-4aa1-89eb-c9296513e820"}
